The Data Rangers: Keeping Chaos at Bay

1. Creating Subsets and Pie chart

# Loading the excel file
data_netflix <- read_excel("netflix_titles.xlsx")

# Creating subsets for 'Movie' and 'TV Show' 
data_movie <- data_netflix %>% filter(type == "Movie")
data_tv <- data_netflix %>% filter(type == "TV Show")
count<-table(data_netflix$type) #this is to see how many are movies in your data and how many are TV shows.
count_df <-as.data.frame(count) #this converts the table to something that ggplot can use

# Renames the column
names(count_df) <-c("type","count") 

# We may also show the percentages
count_df$percent <- count_df$count / sum(count_df$count) * 100

# Creating the pie chart
ggplot(count_df, aes(x = "", y = count, fill = type)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity", color = "white") +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(percent), "%")),  # Here, we add the percentage labels using geom_text
            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5),
            size = 8, 
            fontface = "bold", 
            color = "white") + 
  coord_polar("y") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "orange")) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Content on Netflix: Movies vs. TV Shows", x = NULL, y = NULL, fill = "Category") +
  theme_void()

We see here clearly that 69% (5377) of all the contents in Netflix are movies, while 31% (2410) are TV shows.

The Probability Pilgrims: A Journey Through Monte Carlo

1. OLS Regression

a. Generating sample data

Q: Generate an independent variable that is n=1350, with values from 0 to 100 and a dependent variable that is 2 time of the independent variable with random value drawn from a normal distribution with a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 2.

# We may set seed for replicablity 
set.seed(9823)

# Independent variable (x)
n <- 1350
x<-runif(n, 0, 100)

# Dependent variable (y)
y <- 2*x + rnorm(n, 0, sd = 2)

b. Running the regression

ggplot(data = data.frame(x, y), aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of Simulated Data + Fitted line",
       x = "X", y = "Y")

model0 <- lm(y ~ x)

## printing the results:

# Coeffecients
cat("Intercept (Î²â): ", coef(model0)[1], "\n")
Intercept (Î²â):  0.09468007 
cat("Coefficient for X (Î²â): ", coef(model0)[2], "\n")
Coefficient for X (Î²â):  1.997997 
# Adjusted R-squared
cat("Adjusted R-squared: ", summary(model0)$adj.r.squared, "\n")
Adjusted R-squared:  0.998755 
# F-statistic and p-value
cat("F-statistic:", summary(model0)$fstatistic[1], "\n")
F-statistic: 1082214 
p_val = pf(summary(model0)$fstatistic[1],summary(model0)$fstatistic[2],summary(model0)$fstatistic[3],lower.tail=FALSE)
cat("p-value:", p_val, "\n")
p-value: 0

b.1 Interpretation

The null hypothesis is: the indepdent variable x has no effect on the dependent variable y.

Since the p-value approaches 0, i.e., p-value<0.05, and F-statistics is very large, we reject the null hypothesis. Therefore, there is significant evidence that the variable x affects variable y.

And, since the coefficient is +1.997, this means that that there is a direct relationship between x and y (as x increases, y increases).

The Adjusted R-squared (0.998755) is very close to 1.00, this implies that our fitted line is a very good fit.

set.seed(9823) # we set seed for replicability

## Replication function
sim2<-function(n){
  x<-runif(n, min=0, max=100)
  y <- 2*x + rnorm(n, 0, 2)
  ols<-lm(y~x, data=data.frame(y,x))
  b<-ols$coefficients
  return(b)
}

Slope Seekers: The Quest for Linear Regression

data(beauty)

Bivariate Regression

1. Choosing the dependent and independent variables

I chose lwage as dependent variable and union (membership) as the independent variable. Labor unions usually have more bargaining power in terms of wage negotiation. Unions negotiate contracts with employers which often include higher wages, long-term benefits, and pay increases. While other variables can be used as independent variables, for me, union membership has a stronger basis in affecting wage; hence, it is worth examining as a dependent variable using the bivariate regression.

lwage was chosen instead of wage. When looking at the histogram of wage, there are extreme outliers that skewed the distribution to the right (while not being asked, the histogram of wage is provided below for reference). Taking the logarithm transform of wage helps to normalize the distribution which is generally more desirable for statistical analysis.

With this, our null hypotheses are:

  • Null: Union membership does not affect the log(wage) of employees

  • Alternative: Union membership affects the log(wage) of employees.

Descriptive Statistics and Histogram for union

describe(beauty$union)
   vars    n mean   sd median trimmed mad min max range skew kurtosis   se
X1    1 1260 0.27 0.45      0    0.22   0   0   1     1 1.02    -0.96 0.01

[REPORT]

We know that the variable union is a categorical variable (binary). This means that the interpretation for this descriptive statics is different. For instance, the mean represents the percentage of the people that are a union member (27%) since the sum of the observation is just the number of â1sâ in the observations. The standard deviation does not provide us any meaningful interpretation about the spread of the data since there are only two possible values. This is also the case for the median, min, max, etc.

In the original dataset, the datatype of the variable union is an integer [we used here class(beauty$union) to check]. We may change this to categorical (dummy) variable using the factor() function:

# Here, we created a different variable union_cat to hold the categorical variable for union 
beauty$union_cat <- factor(beauty$union)
## Since union is a categorical variable, we may use geom_bar instead 
ggplot(data = beauty, aes(x = union_cat)) +   # we used union_cat instead of union 
  geom_bar(color = "white", fill = "orange") +    
  scale_x_discrete(labels = c("Non-union", "Union")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Union Membership", 
    x = "Union Membership",
    y = "Count"
  ) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(color = "darkred", size = 14, face = "italic")
  )

We see from this histogram there there are 920 that are not part of any union (73%) and 340 who are part of a union (27%).

3. Run the regression and interpret the results

ggplot(data = beauty, aes(x = union, y = lwage)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "blue") +
  labs(title = "wage vs union",
       x = "union", y = "Wage (ln transformed)")

From the plot, we see that there may be a positive relationship between union membership and wage. We will confirm that using the summary() function below.

# Notice here union was used instead of union_cat
# In R, I noticed that when we use a categorical variable in a linear regression model, R automatically treats it as a factor variable, even if the original variable is of integer type. Hence, it does not matter whether we use union or union_cat. 
model <- lm(lwage ~ union, data = beauty)
summary(model)

Call:

     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max

Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Residual standard error: 0.5853 on 1258 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.03136,   Adjusted R-squared:  0.03059

The coeffecient for union is +0.2342, which means that: all else being equal, union members on average earn 23.64% more in wages compared to non-union members (note here that we use percentage increase instead of units since wage is log transformed).

Furthermore, with the pvalue (2.462e-10) being clearly less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. This means that the there is enough evidence to say that union membership increases the percentage wage of employees. We can also see that the 3-asterisk (***) means that coefficient of union is âhighly significantâ at the 0.001 level.

Meanwhile, the R-squared value is 0.0305. This signifies that the fitted line may not be a good fit for the model. In this case, since we are using a categorical dependent variable, this is expected.

4. Run assumption diagnostics and interpret

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(model)

We see here that the datapoints for Residuals vs Fitted, Scale-Location, and Residuals vs Leverage concentrate on only two x-values (as expected because we are using a binary dependent variable). Ideally, we want to see a random scattering of points around the horizontal line. Clearly, we do not see that here. Hence, this indicate violation of the linearity assumption (in residuals vs fitted) and homoscedasticity (in scale-location). Both of which are violation of the assumptions in OLS model.

In the Q-Q residuals, we can see that there is a deviation (bent upwards) in the straight line. This indicates a indicate skewness and heavy-tailed residuals.

In the residuals vs leverage plot, we cannot extract any meaningful insights here since the residuals are only concentrated into two values in the x-axis. Hence, we cannot pinpoint what values are âinfluentialâ.

Since there are violations of the assumptions in the OLS model, our previous interpretation may be unreliable.

Multivariate Regression

1. Choose what additional independent variables you will add; it is suggested that independent variables be less than 4. Explain why you chose those variables to be added.

I chose to add the variables female and bigcity. Women in the workplace has always been undervalued and paid less throughout history. It is interesting to see if this notion holds in this dataset. On the other hand, people living in the big cities tend to be paid more since the cost of living in big cities are higher. It would be interesting as well to investigate this using this dataset.

The additional hypotheses are therefore:

For female

  • Null: Being female has no significant effect on log(wage)

  • Alternative: Being female has significant effect on log(wage)

For bigcity

  • Null: Living in a big city has no significant effect on log(wage)

  • Alternative: Living in big city has significant effect on log(wage)

The coefficient for union is 0.1647, which means that: all else being equal, union members on average earn 16.48% units increase in wage compared to non-union members. The coefficient for female is -0.52589, which means that females on average earn 52.589% decrease in wage compared to males. The coeffecient for bigcity is 0.24752, which means people living in big cities earn 24.752% increase in wage to compared to people living in non big-city.

The p-values for union, female, and bigcity are all less than 0.05 and are all highly significant at 0.001. This means that we reject all the null hypotheses. Therefore, there is enough evidence to say that:

  • Union membership has significant effect on log(wage)

  • Being female has significant effect on log(wage)

  • Living in big city has significant effect on log(wage)

4. I want you to compare the goodness of fit (Adjusted R-squared, p-value and F-statistics) with your bivariate regression. Is there an improvement?

Bivariate Multivariate
Adjusted R-squared 0.03059 0.2371
p-value 2.462e-10 2.21e-16
F-statistics 40.72 131.4

From the table, we can see clearly that there is an improvement in the goodness of fit. R-squared is now higher, and F-statistics is higher, and the p-value is lower. This suggests that in the bivariate regression, adding the two independent variables allows the model to capture additional variation in the dependent variable that may not have been accounted for by the initial independent variable (union). Also, by incorporating additional independent variables, the model may have became better in explaining the variability in lwage, resulting in smaller residuals and a better fit to the data.

5. Perform Assumption Diagnostics. If you are not sure with the plots, use the tests you learned. You do not have to perform all, unless you are unsure about the four plots and the correlation matrix.

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(model_multi)

Similar with the bivariate regression, we see here that the datapoints for Residuals vs Fitted, Scale-Location, and Residuals vs Leverage concentrate on only very few x-axis values. Clearly, we do not see the random scattering of datapoints around the horizontal line which should be ideal. Hence, this indicate violation of the linearity assumption (in residuals vs fitted) and homoscedasticity (in scale-location). Both of which are violation of the assumptions in OLS model.

In the Q-Q residuals, we can see that there is a deviation (bent upwards) in the straight line. This indicates a indicate skewness and heavy-tailed residuals.

In the residuals vs leverage plot, we cannot extract any meaningful insights since the residuals are only concentrated into few values in the x-axis. Hence, we cannot actually observe which values are considered âinfluentialâ.

We may also use the tests:

# Using the White Test
whitestrap::white_test(model_multi)
White's test results

Null hypothesis: Homoskedasticity of the residuals
Alternative hypothesis: Heteroskedasticity of the residuals
Test Statistic: 6.25
P-value: 0.043958

While close to 0.05, p-value is still less than 0.05. Hence, we reject the null hypothesis. This means that there is heteroskedasticity of the residuals which is a violation of our assumption.

# Using the studentized Breusch-Pagan test
lmtest::bptest(model_multi)

    studentized Breusch-Pagan test

data:  model_multi
BP = 11.037, df = 3, p-value = 0.01153

Again, p-value is less than 0.05. this means that we reject the null hypothesis and this means that heteroskedasticity not present in our data, i.e.Â it violates the assumptions.

Since there are violations in the assumptions, our previous interpretations may not be unreliable.

Data Stewards: Managing Metrics for Econometric Insights

All the parts of the problem set are essential in building the intuition behind using R and applying econometrics in the real world. The first problem regarding data rangers focuses on the basics of data management which is helpful especially in the pre-processing of data. Correctly and efficiently handling data are the first steps in making a reliable program. The technical skills I learned from this portion is not only limited to its application to R, but also in other programming languages where the same intuition commonly applies. Meanwhile, probability pilgrims mostly teach us about the basics of data generating process using R, as well as using R as a tool to run large-scale simulations that cannot normally be done manually. While the technical founadations behind data generating process and Monte Carlo Simulations are very complex (as discussed in ECOMETR), using R to do them made them way less intimidating. Through this part, I learned that the possibilities are seemingly limitless in simulating even large datasets (as long as the computer is capable of it, of course). The bivariate and multivariate regression parts are when we are actually exposed to the application of these statistical techniques to the real world. It is a very meaningful problem since we are able to interpret the relationships among real data using theories that are relatively hard to grasp when learned only using formal mathematics. Finally, the essay portion is a good finisher to collate our insights and synthesize our learning experiences from the problem set. It allows us to not only reflect on what we have done, but also to reflect on the technical skills we have acquired that will most likely be helpful in the future.
